clabGWDevicePublicAccessEnabled.description: This object is defined in the CableLabs TR-181 extension to Device.DeviceInfo. When set to 'true' will indicate that public access, for example Community WIFI, is enabled on this device. When set to 'false', indicates public access is disabled for this device.

clabGWDeviceDNSIpv6QueryForDualMode.name: clabGWDeviceDNSIpv6QueryForDualMode
clabGWDeviceDNSIpv6QueryForDualMode.description: This object provides control over the DNS queries transmitted by LAN clients when the Router is configured in either 'IPv6 Protocol Enabled' or 'Dual Protocol Enabled' modes. When the value of clabGWDeviceDNSIpv6QueryForDualMode is set to 'true', the IPv4 DNS query will be transport layer re-encapsulated into IPv6 for transmission across the Service Provider's network. When set to 'false', the IPv4 DNS query will be transmitted. natively over IPv4. This attribute has no effect if the router is configured for 'IPv4 Protocol Enabled' mode

clabGWMAPDomainTable.name: clabGWMAPDomainTable
clabGWMAPDomainTable.reference: TR-181 Device:2.8 Data Model for TR-069, Device.MAP.Domain
clabGWMAPDomainTable.description: MAP domain settings [MAP]. Each instance models a MAP domain. MAP supports two transport modes, both of which use NAPT44 (modified to use a restricted port range): MAP-E (TransportMode = Encapsulation) uses an IPv4-in-IPv6 tunnel. MAP-T (TransportMode = Translation) uses stateless NAT64.

clabGWMAPDomainBRIPv6Prefix.description: The MAP Border Relay (BR) address or prefix. For MAP-E this is the BR address and therefore MUST be a /128 [MAP]. For MAP-T this is the BR prefix [MAP-T].

clabGWMAPDomainBRIPv6PrefixLen.name: clabGWMAPDomainBRIPv6PrefixLen
clabGWMAPDomainBRIPv6PrefixLen.reference: TR-181 Device:2.8 Data Model for TR-069, Device.MAP.Domain.{i}.BRIPv6Prefix

clabGWMAPDomainDSCPMarkPolicy.name: clabGWMAPDomainDSCPMarkPolicy
clabGWMAPDomainDSCPMarkPolicy.reference: TR-181 Device:2.8 Data Model for TR-069, Device.MAP.Domain.{i}.DSCPMarkPolicy
clabGWMAPDomainDSCPMarkPolicy.description: DSCP with which to mark the outer IP header for traffic that is associated with this MAP domain. Downstream packets are never re-marked. Automatic DSCP marking behavior is a local matter to the device, possibly influenced by other Broadband Forum standards that it supports. A value of -1 indicates copy from the incoming packet. A value of -2 indicates automatic marking of DSCP.

clabGWMAPDomainIncludeSystemPorts.name: clabGWMAPDomainIncludeSystemPorts
clabGWMAPDomainIncludeSystemPorts.reference: TR-181 Device:2.8 Data Model for TR-069, Device.MAP.Domain.{i}.IncludeSystemPorts
clabGWMAPDomainIncludeSystemPorts.description: Whether to include low-numbered (system) ports in the Port-sets. Normally ports in the range [0:2^(16-PSIDOffset)-1] are excluded, e.g. for the default PSIDOffset value of 4, ports [0:4095] are not included in the Port-sets. As specified in [MAP], this parameter is relevant only when PSIDOffset is 0.

clabGWMAPDomainRuleTable.name: clabGWMAPDomainRuleTable

clabGWMAPDomainRuleTable.description: The MAP domain's Mapping Rules [MAP]. The rule with the longest match between its IPv6Prefix and the end-user IPv6Prefix is the Basic Mapping Rule (BMR). Any of the rules (including the BMR) can be a Forwarding Mapping Rule. At most one entry in this table (regardless of whether or not it is enabled) can exist with a given value for Alias. On creation of a new table entry, the CPE MUST choose an initial value for Alias such that the new entry does not conflict with any existing entries.

clabGWMAPDomainRulePSIDOffset.reference: TR-181 Device:2.8 Data Model for TR-069,Device.MAP.Domain.{i}.PSIDOffset but moved on a be on per Rule basis.
clabGWMAPDomainRulePSIDOffset.description: Port-set ID (PSID) offset in bits. The number of Port-sets is 2^PSIDOffset. Corresponds to the [MAP-DHCP] S46_PORTPARAMS (Port Parameters) option's offset field.

clabGWMAPDomainRulePSIDLength.name: clabGWMAPDomainRulePSIDLength
clabGWMAPDomainRulePSIDLength.reference: TR-181 Device:2.8 Data Model for TR-069, Device.MAP.Domain.{i}.PSIDLength but moved on a be on per Rule basis.
clabGWMAPDomainRulePSIDLength.description: The length in bits of the Port-set id (PSID) configured in the PSID parameter. Corresponds to the [MAP-DHCP] S46_PORTPARAMS (Port Parameters) option's PSID-len field moved on a be on per Rule level.

clabGWMAPDomainRulePSID.name: clabGWMAPDomainRulePSID
clabGWMAPDomainRulePSID.reference: TR-181 Device:2.8 Data Model for TR-069, Device.MAP.Domain.{i}.PSIDLength but moved on a be on per Rule basis.
clabGWMAPDomainRulePSID.description: Port-set ID (PSID) to use in preference to the value extracted from the Embedded Address (EA) bits. Only the high order PSIDLength bits of the PSID value are used, so the parameter is ignored when PSIDLength is zero. Corresponds to the [MAP-DHCP] S46_PORTPARAMS (Port Parameters) option's PSID field.

clabGWMAPDomainIfStatus.name: clabGWMAPDomainIfStatus
clabGWMAPDomainIfStatus.reference: TR-181 Device:2.8 Data Model for TR-069, Device.MAP.Domain.{i}.Interface.Status
clabGWMAPDomainIfStatus.description: The status of this TunnelInterface. When Enable is false then Status SHOULD normally be Down (or NotPresent or Error if there is a fault condition on the interface). When Enable is false then Status SHOULD normally be Down (or NotPresent or Error if there is a fault condition on the interface). When Enable is changed to true then Status SHOULD change to Up if and only if the interface is able to transmit and receive network traffic; it SHOULD change to Dormant if and only if the interface is operable but is waiting for external actions before it can transmit and receive network traffic (and subsequently change to Up if still operable when the expected actions have completed); it SHOULD change to LowerLayerDown if and only if the interface is prevented from entering the Up state because one or more of the interfaces beneath it is down; it SHOULD remain in the Error state if there is an error or other fault condition detected on the interface; it SHOULD remain in the NotPresent state if the interface has missing (typically hardware) components; it SHOULD change to Unknown if the state of the interface can not be determined for some reason.
